            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p>The Chaldaic Dialect has a very close resemblance<lb/> to the Syriac: hence they are
                both frequently referred<lb/> to under the common name of Aramean. Its
                alpha=<lb/>betical character &amp; mode of writing are the same with<lb/> the
                Hebrew. Its conjugations are I Peal (Kal. H.) pass.<lb/> Ethpeel: II Pael (piel. H)
                pass. Ethpaal: III aphel<lb/> (Highest H.)</p>
            <p>The Syriac vowels are five. viz.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Pethotho <add>?</add> or <add>?</add> a</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Rebotso <add>?</add> or <add>?</add> e</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Hebotso <add>?</add> i</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Zekopho <add>?</add> o</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Etsotso <add>?</add> or <add>?</add> u</p>
            <p>The three first characters in the left hand column are<lb/> written either above or
                below the line. The Syriac has<lb/> no sign for dagech nor for sheva. The linea
                occultans<lb/> = is placed under a letter to show that it is mute; thus<lb/>
                <add>?</add> bath (not barth) a daughter. The other diacritical<lb/> sepsis are of
                minor importance. The conjugations are<lb/> I Pial pass Ethpeel. II Pael, pass.
                Ethpael; III aphel.</p>
            <p>The Arabic vowels are only three: viz.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Fatha <add>?</add> a, e.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Kesra <add>?</add> e, i.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Dharma <add>?</add> o, u. These vowels become<lb/> long when
                followed by a homogeneous quiescent. When<lb/> followed by any other quiescent, they
                form dipthongs;<lb/> as <add>?</add>'s <hi rend="underline">lau</hi>. The
                diacritical signs are</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Jesm <add>?</add> or quiescent sheva</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Teshdid <add>?</add> or Dagesh forte</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Hauza <add>?</add> placed over Elif when radical</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Nesta <add>?</add> placed over initial Elif, showing<lb/> that the
                word if joined in pronunciation with the pre-<lb/>ceding medda <add>?</add> placed
                over Elif as a sign of<lb/> prolongation.</p>
            <p>Nunnation or double final vowels, <add>?</add> showing that<lb/> they are to be
                pronounced <hi rend="underline">au</hi>, <hi rend="underline">eu</hi> or <hi
                    rend="underline">iu</hi>, on <hi rend="underline">or</hi> un. It occurs
                only<lb/> in the Koran &amp; in poetry. Conjugations are very numerous.</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>The <hi rend="underline">Persians</hi> use the arabic alphabet with the<lb/> addition
                of <add>?</add> for <hi rend="underline">p</hi>. <add>?</add> for <hi
                    rend="underline">ch</hi> as in church: <add>?</add> or<lb/>
                <add>?</add> for <hi rend="underline">g</hi> hard: and <hi rend="underline"
                        ><add>?</add> for zh</hi>.</p>
            <p>Chald. <persName>Dan.</persName> 2. 4 to 7. 28.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Ezra</persName> 48 to 6.18 also 7.12-27_S2.5 Ges.
                Gram.</p>
